Day 2 – JWT Authentication

JWT (JSON Web Token)

JWT stands for JSON Web Token.

It is a secure token used for authentication and authorization between a client (browser/mobile app) and a server.

After a user logs in successfully, the server generates a JWT token and sends it to the client. The client stores this token and sends it with every request to prove its identity.

Authentication

Authentication means verifying who the user is.

Example:

· User enters email and password.

· Server checks whether the credentials are correct.

· If valid, the server generates a JWT token.

· The client uses this token for future requests.

Authorization

Authorization means checking what the authenticated user is allowed to access.

Example:

· An Admin can add or delete users.

· A Normal User can only view their own data.

JWT helps identify the user so the server can decide what actions are permitted.

Encryption

Encryption is the process of converting readable data into an unreadable format to keep it secure.

Only someone with the correct key can decrypt and read the original data.

Example:

Original Data

Hello


Encrypted Data

A8kL9@#xP

Decryption

Decryption is the process of converting encrypted data back into its original readable form.

Example:

Encrypted Data

A8kL9@#xP

Decrypted Data

Hello

Hashing

Hashing converts data into a fixed-length value called a hash.

Unlike encryption, hashing cannot be reversed.

It is mainly used for storing passwords securely in the database.

Example:

Password

admin123

Hashed Password

$2a$10$H4k3...

When a user logs in:

· The entered password is hashed.

· The server compares it with the stored hashed password.

· If both hashes match, the user is authenticated.


